english:
  title: A Record of the Hall of Serene Countenance
  author: Lee Cheom
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When harmony and gentleness accumulate within, their brilliance shines outward. Thus only when the heart and vital energy are balanced does the countenance become serene. The heart moves and manifests in the face—external things shape it so. In mourning robes, sorrow appears on the face; in court regalia, respect shows forth; in armor, an air of unassailable dignity. Yet when a man responds to these circumstances and his heart returns to balance, showing neither arrogance nor miserliness, radiating warmth like jade—only the gentleman can achieve this.

    Wu Xiansheng of Douhyeon possesses a broad and magnanimous mind, a vast and far-reaching bearing. As keeper of the academy, he penetrated the principles of human nature and destiny, understood the meaning of advance and retreat. He entrusted gain and loss to Heaven, accepting fortune and circumstance with equanimity. Having withdrawn from office, he has spent years in his later years south of Happo Garrison. One day he came to visit me, requesting that I name his hall. I inscribed it "Serene Countenance"—for here, Master Wu resides with an open heart and composed spirit, his breath steady and his energy at peace. Benevolence and righteousness glow upon his face, and a pure, harmonious radiance fills his being. Thus I chose this name.

    To follow principle is to find joy; when joy stirs, the heart awakens in gladness, and then the countenance becomes serene. Conversely, without joy comes worry; worry brings a furrowed brow—how could the face be serene then? Moreover, a hall is a place of leisure and rest. In ancient times, when the Master himself dwelt at ease, he was serene and content. Tao Yuanming wrote in his "Return to the Fields": "Gazing upon the boughs in the courtyard gladdens my countenance." The sages and worthies of old were neither idle nor harsh; thus the balanced, harmonious spirit visible in their moments of repose teaches us what the gentleman cultivates.

    When a man is joyful, a gentle ease settles over him; as contentment deepens, he begins to hum and sway; in that swaying, hands begin to dance and feet to prance without his knowing. Where harmonious energy gathers, all blessings converge—and Master Wu embodies this. Those who fail to do so are either slack or severe, heedless in solitude; they know shame in the hidden room. But Master Wu guards against this.

    As for those who exhaust their bodies in the pursuit of wealth or torment their hearts in poverty—blushing with fear of loss and desperate in their grasping, they have no time to cultivate serenity. How could their faces ever become serene? If such people could but hear the name of this hall and take it as a mirror, perhaps they might escape the trap of vain fortune.
  footnotes:
    - Douhyeon (斗峴) and Happo Garrison (合浦鎭) are place names in Korea, indicating Wu Xiansheng's retirement location.
    - The reference to "Master" (夫子) here refers to Confucius and his exemplary comportment.
    - Tao Yuanming's "Return to the Fields" (歸去來辭) is a celebrated poem about retirement and finding peace in simple living.
